<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-permutations-ii" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Permutations II</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>3.0 Statistics and Probability</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>3.1 Permutations and Combinations</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>Perform permutations involving identical items and constrained arrangements.</p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>11</p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>40 minutes</p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>10 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>To realize that swapping two identical items does not create a new arrangement.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>Provide students with letter cards for the word "BOB". Ask them to list all unique arrangements. They will find fewer than <m>3!</m> because the two 'B's are identical.</p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <title>The Identical Twins Problem</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                You have 3 flags to hang on a pole: 2 Red flags (identical) and 1 Blue flag.
                <ol>
                    <li>If the Red flags were different (e.g., Red1 and Red2), how many total arrangements would there be?</li>
                    <li>List all the visually different ways you can actually hang these flags.</li>
                    <li>Why is your list in step 2 shorter than the answer in step 1?</li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <insight>
        <title>Permutations with Identical Items</title>
        <p>
            When some items in a set are identical, swapping them does not result in a new distinguishable permutation. To correct for this, we divide the total permutations by the factorial of the number of identical items.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>The Formula:</strong>
            <line>For <m>n</m> objects where <m>p</m> are of one kind, <m>q</m> are of another, and <m>r</m> are of another, the number of unique permutations is:</line>
            <me>P = \frac{n!}{p! q! r! \dots}</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>Example Logic:</strong>
            <line>To arrange the letters in "APPLE", we have 5 letters total, but 'P' repeats twice.</line>
            <me>P = \frac{5!}{2!} = \frac{120}{2} = 60 \text{ ways.}</me>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>1. In how many ways can you arrange 5 Red balls and 3 Blue balls in a row?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Total items (<m>n</m>) = 8.
                Repeats: 5 Red (<m>5!</m>), 3 Blue (<m>3!</m>).
                <me>P = \frac{8!}{5! 3!} = \frac{8 \times 7 \times 6 \times 5!}{5! \times (3 \times 2 \times 1)} = \frac{336}{6} = 56 \text{ ways.}</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>2. How many unique arrangements can be made using all the letters in the word <strong>STATISTICS</strong>?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Total letters = 10.
                Count the repeats: S (3), T (3), I (2).
                <me>P = \frac{10!}{3! 3! 2!} = \frac{3,628,800}{6 \times 6 \times 2} = 50,400 \text{ ways.}</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>3. To move from point A to point B, a robot must move 4 steps Right (R) and 3 steps Up (U). How many different paths can the robot take?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                This is a permutation of the sequence RRRRUUU.
                Total steps = 7. Repeats: R(4), U(3).
                <me>P = \frac{7!}{4! 3!} = \frac{7 \times 6 \times 5}{3 \times 2 \times 1} = 35 \text{ paths.}</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>4. How many ways can the letters in "LEMON" be arranged if the letter 'L' must always be at the beginning?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                If 'L' is fixed in the first position, we only need to arrange the remaining 4 unique letters (E, M, O, N).
                <me>P = 4! = 24 \text{ ways.}</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>5. There are 3 Math books and 2 Science books. In how many ways can they be arranged on a shelf if the Math books must stay together?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                1. Treat the 3 Math books as one "block". We now have 1 block + 2 Science books = 3 items to arrange: <m>3!</m>.
                2. Within the block, the 3 Math books can be arranged in <m>3!</m> ways.
                <me>\text{Total} = 3! \times 3! = 6 \times 6 = 36 \text{ ways.}</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>1. How many ways can the letters of the word "BANANA" be arranged?</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>Total = 6. Repeats: A(3), N(2). <me>P = \frac{6!}{3! 2!} = \frac{720}{6 \times 2} = 60</me></p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>2. A coin is flipped 10 times. How many sequences of outcomes have exactly 8 Heads and 2 Tails?</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><me>\frac{10!}{8! 2!} = \frac{10 \times 9}{2} = 45 \text{ sequences.}</me></p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>3. In how many ways can 4 identical Red pens and 4 identical Blue pens be distributed to 8 students if each gets one pen?</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><me>\frac{8!}{4! 4!} = \frac{8 \times 7 \times 6 \times 5}{24} = 70 \text{ ways.}</me></p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>4. How many unique 7-digit phone numbers can be formed using the digits 5, 5, 5, 8, 8, 1, 1?</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><me>\frac{7!}{3! 2! 2!} = \frac{5040}{6 \times 2 \times 2} = 210 \text{ numbers.}</me></p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>5. Find the number of arrangements of the letters "BEEKEEPER" where all the 'E's are together.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Treat "EEEE" as one block. Remaining letters: B, K, P, R. 
                    Total items to arrange = 5.
                    <m>5! = 120</m> ways. (Note: Internal arrangement of 'E's is <m>4!/4! = 1</m>).
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-methods.ptx" />

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/reflection.ptx"/>
</section>